                                    <material>Dark whinstone</material> 
                                    <objectType>Class I Pictish symbol stone/menhir</objectType>                      
                                    <dimensions unit="m">                                         
                                            <height>1.07</height>
                                            <width>1.27</width>
                                            <depth>0.91</depth>
                                     </dimensions>         
                                </support>
                                <condition>The stone is a large roughly triangular mass broken into several pieces, but the extant carving is well-preserved (Forsyth 1996, 103).</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The smoothest face of the stone is incised with two <rs type="decoration">Pictish symbols</rs>, a <rs type="decoration">crescent-and-V-rod</rs> and a <rs type="decoration">snake-and-Z-rod</rs>, and an ogham inscription runs parrallel with the left edge (Forsyth 1996, 103).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The ogham strokes appear to have been <rs type="execution"  key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs> and subsequently smoothed (Gordon 1956, 44). According to Gordon's description, both the symbols and the ogham inscription were <q>improved to such an extent that its shallow grooves are smooth and regular, contrasting clearly with the flat but roughish surface of the boulder</q> (ibid). Individual strokes as well as letters are tightly packed (Forsyth 1996, 112). The stem-line is arranged vertically on the face, is more or less straight, though it wavers slightly, and it runs roughly parallel with the stone's left-hand edge (Forsyth 1996, 109). It is 3cm across at the surface, but only 1cm at the bottom of the channel (Forsyth 1996, 105).
                                <height/>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
