             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="sga" resp="#LH"><!--update lang here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/>
                    ᚔᚏᚐᚈᚐᚇᚇᚑᚐᚏᚓᚅᚄ<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="sga" xml:space="preserve" resp="#LH">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:up"/>
                    IRATADDOARENS<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app n="1">
                        <note>While the transliteration of the ogham inscription is unambiguous, the interpretation remains uncertain. The most likely interpretation is a single personal name, taking into consideration the length of the text. However, it is uncertain whether the thirteen letters are a complete text as they are, or whether there are any letters missing from the end (Forsyth 1996, 112-3).</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <!--<div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p></p>
            </div>-->
            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The dimensions are approximate metric equivalents of dimensions listed by Romilly Allen (Allen 1903, 507). Forsyth noted that precise measurements are difficult to obtain given the irregular shape of the stone (Forsyth 1996, 103-4).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="2"><p>The original orientation of the stone is assumed to have been vertical. Given that the ogham inscription is situated vertically relative to the intact sides of the stone, it is further assumed that the original orientation of the inscription was vertical as well despite its current diagonal axis (Forsyth 1996, 104).</p>
                    </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
